As the identity oi a painter shews itself in certain peculiarities oi colouring or manipulatim, so does that of a poet in peculi- arities os diction and rhythm. But perhaps more attention is nowadays bestowed upon the case oi the painter, which appeals to the eye, than upon that oi the poet, which must be decided by the ear. Yet that the diction and rhythm os a poem are among its important characteristics will hardly be denied by a carelul reader of the Aeneid or Paradira Lost. In the caseos Lucan this lineos inquiry has special interest: for, though it is easy to note in detail the numerous traces oi Vergil's influence on the writer os the Pharsalia, itis none the less true that the effect of the whole poem is anything but Vergilian. Indeed it cannot be said to bear a general resemblance to any other work in ancient literature that has come down to us. It stands between the old Rome and the new, not only in its subject and spirit but also in its rhythm and diction.
